          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"week_number\":1,\"phase_type\":\"Base\",\"weekly_target_km\":60,\"is_deload_week\":false,\"sunday\":{\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"notes\":\"22–24 km at easy pace (5:08–5:53/km). Relaxed effort, conversational pace. Focus on time on feet, not speed. This anchors your week and mirrors your current long run fitness.\"},\"monday\":{\"slot_type\":\"Rest\",\"workout_type\":null,\"notes\":\"Full rest day. You've earned it after Sunday's long run. Quality recovery here directly feeds Tuesday's quality work.\"},\"tuesday\":{\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"Tempo\",\"notes\":\"10 km total: 2 km easy warm-up, 6 km at threshold pace (4:16/km), 2 km easy cool-down. Threshold work builds your lactate ceiling — critical for sustaining marathon pace.\"},\"wednesday\":{\"slot_type\":\"Rest\",\"workout_type\":null,\"notes\":\"Rest or light walking only. Protecting Wednesday keeps the quality high on Thursday without compounding fatigue.\"},\"thursday\":{\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"notes\":\"14 km easy (5:08–5:53/km). Aerobic volume day. Keep the effort genuinely easy — this is where your aerobic engine grows, not where you prove fitness.\"},\"friday\":{\"slot_type\":\"Rest\",\"workout_type\":null,\"notes\":\"Rest day. With 4 run days this week, Friday is a buffer between Thursday's volume and Saturday's workout.\"},\"saturday\":{\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"Interval\",\"notes\":\"10 km total: 2 km warm-up, 5 × 1 km at interval pace (3:56/km) with 90-sec jog recoveries, 2 km cool-down. VO2max stimulus. These intervals are what push your ceiling higher over the coming months.\"},\"week_summary\":\"Welcome to your marathon build, Priya. Week 1 sits right at your current 60 km baseline — no jump in volume, just a well-structured distribution of stress and recovery across your 4 run days. The pattern this week (Long Run → Tempo → Easy → Intervals) is the backbone of your training: one long aerobic effort, one lactate threshold session, one easy aerobic day, and one VO2max stimulus. Each piece has a distinct physiological purpose, and together they target the 3:15 finish that your half marathon fitness strongly supports. Your 1:32 HM translates to a predicted marathon around 3:12–3:16, so 3:15 is ambitious but grounded in real data. This first week is about establishing the rhythm and confirming the paces feel right. How do the assigned paces feel when you look at them — anything that jumps out as too easy or too aggressive?\"}"
        }
      ]
